  "prompt": "What is the acceptable TDS level of drinking water?",
  "response": "The acceptable Total Dissolved Solids (TDS) level in drinking water varies by guideline, but generally, the World Health Organization (WHO) recommends the following:\n\n- **0-300 mg/L**: Excellent drinking water quality.\n- **300-600 mg/L**: Good drinking water quality.\n- **600-900 mg/L**: Fair drinking water quality; palatability can be affected.\n- **900-1200 mg/L**: Poor drinking water quality; may not be acceptable for drinking.\n- **Above 1200 mg/L**: Very poor quality; not recommended for drinking.\n\nIt's important to note that while TDS is a useful measure of overall water quality, it does not indicate the presence of specific harmful substances. Therefore, other tests might be necessary to ensure the safety of drinking water.",
